# API / Route handler context

You are editing **API routes** or **route handlers**. Combine your knowledge with project rules.

## Use your knowledge (no need to paste long docs)

- REST semantics (status codes, idempotency, GET vs POST)
- Next.js Route Handlers (Request, Response, dynamic vs static)
- Input validation and sanitization
- Error handling and safe error responses (no stack traces to client)
- Security: no sensitive data in responses, CORS if needed

## Project-specific – read only these sections when needed

- **docs/CODING_STANDARDS.md §11** – Error handling (try/catch, no console.error in prod)
- **§3** – TypeScript (no `any`, proper types for body/query)
- **§5** – Back-end performance (fast responses, avoid N+1, validate input)
- **§17** – Code quality back-end (validation, status codes, no sensitive data in responses); SonarQube

## Quick checks

- Validate and parse request body/query; return 400 for invalid input
- Return correct status codes (200, 201, 400, 401, 404, 500)
- Do not leak internal errors or stack traces to the client
- Use TypeScript types for request/response payloads
